  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers think of preparation as a discrete event before launch: declutter, paint a few rooms, get the lawn cut, photograph the property, list it. The campaign then proceeds, and at some point a buyer offers and signs a contract. What happens between contract signing and settlement is rarely discussed in detail, but it matters more than most sellers realise. The property must be delivered at settlement in the same condition it was at the date of contract, fair wear and tear excepted. If the lawn is now waist high, the bathroom mouldy, or the timber deck stained from a storm, the buyer has legitimate grounds to renegotiate, request repairs, or in extreme cases threaten termination.</p>

      <p>The principle is straightforward. The marketing photos and the property condition at exchange set the buyer's expectation. Anything materially worse at the pre-settlement inspection becomes a problem. The way sellers avoid that problem is to treat ongoing maintenance as a planned line item from launch through to settlement, not as a reactive scramble in the final week.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Queensland contractual baseline</h2>
      <p>Under the standard REIQ contract used for most Brisbane residential sales, the seller must deliver the property at settlement in the same condition as at the contract date, fair wear and tear excepted. "Same condition" is broader than most people assume. It includes the garden, lawn, and external grounds, the interior condition and cleanliness, the condition of fixtures and fittings, and outdoor areas such as decks, patios, pergolas, and pool surrounds. If the buyer's pre-settlement inspection finds the property materially different, the buyer's solicitor can raise it as a contractual issue.</p>

      <p>"Fair wear and tear" covers the small expected changes from normal use. It does not cover deterioration from neglect. A six week campaign where the lawn is left to grow knee high, the pool turns green, or the gutters clog and overflow during a storm is not fair wear and tear. It is a failure to maintain the property as represented.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The lawn and garden across a Brisbane campaign</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's subtropical climate is the single biggest maintenance variable. From October through to April, lawns grow fast. A property photographed with a freshly mown lawn in week one will look very different in week three if no one has touched it. Plan for weekly mowing across the campaign, edging and weeding every two to three weeks, and make sure the lawn is freshly cut two to three days before every open home. A gardener at $40 to $80 per visit is a small line item compared to the price impact of a buyer walking up to a property that looks neglected.</p>

      <p>Garden beds need attention too. Remove dropped leaves, top up mulch where it has thinned, and prune anything that has grown into pathways or windows. The first thing a buyer sees on approach is the front yard. If the front yard tells them the seller has lost interest, they will price that into their offer or their pre-settlement complaints.</p>

      <p>Storm season runs from October to April in southeast Queensland. After heavy rain or strong winds, walk the property within 24 hours. Pick up fallen branches, clear gutters if leaves have built up, check for any tile or roofing damage, and photograph anything that has changed. Documenting the property's condition through the campaign protects the seller if a buyer later raises an issue.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interior maintenance through the open home cycle</h2>
      <p>Open homes are weekly performances. Each one needs the property to look the same as it did on day one. A weekly clean, ideally the day before each open home, maintains the photography standard. Bathrooms and kitchens get the most scrutiny from buyers, so allocate the most time to those. Made beds, fresh towels, clean benches, and a faint fresh smell rather than a chemical one are the simple cues that tell buyers the property is cared for.</p>

      <p>Address small defects immediately rather than letting them accumulate. Loose door handles, chipped paint near skirtings, marks on walls, a noisy ceiling fan, a sticking door, a dripping tap. Each one on its own is minor. Five of them together, observed at an open home or pre-settlement inspection, change the buyer's perception from "well maintained" to "the seller has stopped caring." A handyman for two hours every fortnight across the campaign is cheaper than the discount a buyer will negotiate for a list of small defects.</p>

      <p>Air the property out before every inspection. Open windows for an hour, run the air conditioning briefly if needed, and replace any bins that have been used. Brisbane's humidity makes interiors smell stale quickly, especially in homes that have been closed up during the week.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who pays for what</h2>
      <p>Routine maintenance during the campaign is the seller's cost. The lawn, the cleaning, the small repairs, the pool servicing if there is a pool. None of that is recoverable from the buyer because it is part of selling the property properly.</p>

      <p>Emergencies sit in a different category. A burst pipe, major storm damage, a tree falling through the roof, or a break-in are events the seller is responsible to address but may be claimable on insurance. The important thing is to act fast: notify the insurer immediately, photograph everything, do not start permanent repairs without insurer approval, and tell the buyer's solicitor through your own solicitor if the event is material. Trying to hide damage and hope the buyer does not notice at pre-settlement inspection is a worse outcome than disclosing it and resolving it transparently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the seller has already vacated</h2>
      <p>If the seller has moved out before or during the campaign, ongoing maintenance becomes harder. There is no one in the house noticing that the lawn has grown, the bins need emptying, or the bathroom needs a clean before Saturday's open home. The solution is to engage a small team and a routine: a gardener weekly, a cleaner weekly, and a trusted person (a neighbour, a friend, or in some cases the agent) doing a property check between visits.</p>

      <p>Vacant properties also raise the question of styling. An empty property photographs poorly, looks smaller, and gives buyers nothing to anchor their imagination to. Rental furniture and styling for the campaign is a typical investment of $3,000 to $8,000 for a six to eight week period and consistently delivers a return well above the cost. If the seller has vacated, styled rooms also look the same week after week, which simplifies maintenance compared to a lived-in property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenanted properties during a sale campaign</h2>
      <p>If the property is being sold tenanted or with the tenant still in place during the campaign, maintenance responsibility splits between seller and tenant. The tenant is responsible for day-to-day cleanliness under the lease. The tenant is not responsible for campaign-level presentation: the lawn cut to a higher standard, the bathrooms scrubbed before each open home, the styling and staging.</p>

      <p>Negotiate access for professional cleaning before open homes if the tenant agrees, and consider reasonable compensation for the tenant's inconvenience. A small reduction in rent for the campaign period, or covering the cost of a cleaner, often produces better cooperation than insisting the tenant lift their game. Tenants who feel respected during a sale typically present the property better than tenants who feel inconvenienced and ignored.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Storm season specifics</h2>
      <p>Selling between October and April in Brisbane carries weather risk that needs to be planned for, not reacted to. Clean gutters before launch and again midway through the campaign. Secure or remove loose outdoor items such as umbrellas, planters, and small furniture before any forecast severe weather. Photograph the property after each significant rain event so any later claim by a buyer can be checked against documented evidence.</p>

      <p>If the campaign extends into a multi-week severe weather period, talk to the agent about whether to pause open homes or push them as scheduled. Most buyers attend open homes in any weather, but flooded driveways or fallen trees on the property are good reasons to reschedule. A shorter pause, well managed, is better than a poorly attended open home where the property is not at its best.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The pre-settlement inspection standard</h2>
      <p>Buyers in Queensland typically inspect the property one to three days before settlement. The purpose of that inspection is to confirm the property is in the same condition as at the contract date, with all chattels included as agreed and nothing materially different. If the buyer's solicitor raises an issue from the pre-settlement inspection, the seller's solicitor will need to address it, and there are limited days available before settlement to do so.</p>

      <p>A useful seller habit is to walk the property the day before the buyer's inspection. Look at it through the buyer's eyes. Is the lawn cut? Are bins put away? Are all the agreed inclusions still in place? Has anything been damaged or moved? Catching a problem the day before the inspection means the seller has time to fix it before the buyer arrives. Catching a problem after the buyer raises it means a rushed negotiation under time pressure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Budgeting maintenance for a typical six week campaign</h2>
      <p>For a standard Brisbane home with a lawn and garden, the realistic maintenance budget across a six week campaign sits in this range:</p>

      <p>Lawn and garden across the campaign: $300 to $500. Weekly interior cleaning: $600 to $1,000. Miscellaneous repairs and supplies (paint touch-ups, replacement bulbs, handyman hours): $200 to $500. Pool servicing if applicable: $200 to $400. Total maintenance budget for a typical six week campaign: roughly $1,100 to $2,400. For higher-end properties or longer campaigns, double those figures.</p>

      <p>Sellers who try to economise on this line item almost always end up paying more in price negotiation or pre-settlement disputes than they would have spent on maintenance. The maintenance budget is not optional. It is a small percentage of the sale price that protects the rest of the sale price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The framework: treat the campaign as a performance</h2>
      <p>The simplest mental model for campaign maintenance is to treat the whole period from launch to settlement as a single repeating performance. Every open home is a performance. Every photograph in the listing represents what the property should look like at every showing. The pre-settlement inspection is the closing performance. Buyers compare each performance to the original promise.</p>

      <p>Investing in consistent presentation across the campaign, rather than sporadic bursts of effort followed by neglect, almost always produces a better result. The discipline of weekly maintenance is small compared to the alternative: a buyer using a deteriorated property at pre-settlement to negotiate a discount, request repairs, or threaten termination. Sellers who plan maintenance from launch through to settlement consistently report fewer pre-settlement issues, more straightforward final negotiations, and a smoother settlement.</p>

